Wait, Wait, Wait, now M24,<br>
At our local VFW there is a pecking order, 1st Marines, then all the other branches. We're even an equal opportunity employer and include a spot for the Coast Guard Reserves, Marines have their own parking area nearest the bar.<br><br>
No, I can count the times I have been in them, the one where I live, was started several years ago when they needed a vet to sign the papers, no one else was available so I did so. Became the first commander of the post but never attended a meeting, I wouldn't comply with their rituals and other forms of order. As soon as we were chartered we found someone to take over and its been quite successful ever since. One the outside walls are scenes representing and honoring the various branches of service including an Army Vietnam scene.<br>
It is very acceptable to Vietnam veterans and when we had our reunion we choose that place for our initial gathering place. They would have gone all out for us, if I had allowed them too, but since we hadn't seen each other in over 30 years I asked them not too. Still three local newspapers showed up and all wrote nice stories about our reunion. The post treated us with honor, and it was a great homecoming for many of us that never experienced such a thing. Perhaps a national day of honor for Vietnam veterans should be emphasized at some of these watering holes.<br>
The local American Legion in our area is also quite receptive to VN vets, but the majority at both of these posts are old gizzards from WW II or Korea that don't understand the war we fought, they don't understand what we experienced as individuals because they fought as large military units, much like many after 1969 did in Nam. <br>
The local American Legion had selected my daughter as girl state and they recently honored her, but a couple of hours in that place and we couldn't wait to get home to shower because of the smell of smoke from the bar.<br>
I have not looked into Vietnam Veterans of America yet, don't know if they meet in drinking closets or not, but most Vietnam vets seem to be seeking something more then what the VFW or American Legion have to offer<br>

